[[File:8kyocanoe8tj.gif|thumb]] '''Dufuna Canoe''' is a [[canoe]] discovered in 1987 by a [[Fulani]] cattle herdsman a few kilometers from the village of Dufuna in the [[Fune]] Local Government Area, not far from the [[Komadugu Gana River]], in [[Yobe State]], [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Garba | first1 = Abubakar | year = 1996 | title = The architecture and chemistry of a dug-out: the Dufuna Canoe in ethno-archaeological perspective | url = http://publikationen.ub.uni-frankfurt.de/oai/container/index/docId/1859 | journal = Berichte des Sonderforschungsbereichs | volume = 268 | issue = 8| pages = 193–200 }}</ref><ref name="canoe2">(16 September 2002). [http://business.highbeam.com/3548/article-1G1-91662011/dufuna-canoe-bridge-across-8000-years Dufuna Canoe: A Bridge Across 8,000 Years], ''[[Daily Trust]]'' (All Africa Global Media via COMTEX)</ref> Radiocarbon dating of a sample of charcoal found near the site dates the canoe at 8500 to 8000 years old, linking the site to [[Lake Chad|Lake Mega Chad]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gumnior|first1=Maren|last2=Thiemeyer|first2=Heinrich|title=Holocene fluvial dynamics in the NE Nigerian Savanna|journal=Quaternary International|date=2003|volume=111|page=54|doi=10.1016/s1040-6182(03)00014-4 }}</ref>
It is the oldest boat to be discovered in Africa, and the second oldest known worldwide.<ref name=trillo>Trillo, Richard (2008) [https://books.google.ca/books?id=TL1q6BiISt8C&pg=PT2640 "The Rough Guide to West Africa"] ''Penguin.'' Section: Nigeria Part 3:14.5 the north and northeast Maiduguri (pages unnumbered).</ref> The canoe is currently in [[Damaturu]], the state capital.<ref name=trillo/>
